A duel of the blade: MP3 players versus cell phones.
We'll help you choose
While almost every cell phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can be used to make a phone call.
It seems clear that it's better to buy a phone.
Still, there are many reasons why a person might want to get a separate MP3 player.
The choice depends entirely on the use to which it is put and the needs of the future owner.
It's probably not easy to get a high-end, high-priced stereo to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulence album.
Firstly, such musical products are not shown on the discs, but there is no objective reason for this from a quality point of view.
However, if your shelves are filled with art rock, jazz, or blues bakelite records, you may be dreaming of a turntable like this.
This is similarly designed for travel, which is compressed -- simplified to MP3 music.
There are price and quality categories here.
Some people may find it unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan may find it difficult to accept a twenty-crown market headset.
Two extremes, with enough room for everyone.
It's a wide selection.
Battery life is important too
Some of the best music players can do more than just play music, they can do what most cell phones don't do.
No modern device is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to its primary functions of calling and texting, it can play music and video, record both, has a better-than-normal camera, and can even navigate.
And if you take into account smartphones and communicators, you'll also have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no television can take pictures.
Well, multi-function phones have their drawbacks.
The more features you use on your phone, the more times the display sends it to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy drainers.
Few mobile devices can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, most are much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
So, if you're using a cheap cell phone, you can expect that they won't play for more than a few hours.
If you are using a telephone, get a charger for your workplace for safety - even for expensive devices.
MP3 players won't have that problem, even the worst ones can last at least nine hours of continuous play on a single charge.
The next problem is when you're uploading music to your phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector and, moreover, not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course, the music can be recorded directly to the memory card, but few card readers can handle the miniature memory cards used in phones without an adapter.
With a few exceptions, the player (iPod) does not require any special software.
All you have to do is load the device with music from your computer via USB.
Most mobile phones and players also create their own music library, organized by artist, album, genre, or user rating.
Some devices only display fascicles similar to Windows Explorer, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with OS).
Players are easier to handle, cell phones know more
When selecting a specific piece of equipment, you should first consider the battery life, the memory capacity, the quality and type of the audio output, and of course the ease of handling.
If music is your primary background and you listen to it for only a short time each day, such as on the tram, any MP3 player on your cell phone is fine.
And now, any mobile phone can do that.
You don't have to pay much attention to the music formats your phone or player can play.
All of them can handle MP3s, and the vast majority of the music that you get will be in that format.
MP3 is one of the most common formats, and most devices can handle WMA music.
AAC (a format used by Apple and its iPod) is less common.
Right-hand mobiles also make it possible to buy music online, for example.
Simply visit the relevant websites of the provider (or other service providers) via the mobile Internet and buy the song or album.
This service in itself can be a compelling argument for the acquisition of music mobile.
Unfortunately, the service providers' offerings are limited and usually limited to one-year radio stations.
Those prices aren't the lowest.
In general, however, it is likely that this particular way of selling music (whether via GSM, the Internet or wireless) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their mobile device with them at all times.
Whenever he feels like listening to something, he's going to reach into his cell phone while the forgotten MP3 player is lying around.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry your headphones or at least your speakers.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker, which is available on almost all cell phones but few MP3 players.
For many, the biggest advantage of music phones will probably be price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than 3,000 kroner.
Between three and four thousand crowns, you can get a decent enough Walkman.
But for the most part, you're limited by the lack of a conventional headphone output.
The best and technically most equipped telephones with the traditional 3.5 mm diameter hole-in headphones can cost up to fifteen thousand kroner.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, that they are easy to handle.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest - players (see our selection) are really the ones that everyone can handle.
Minimal function, handling similar to the previously usual cassette recorder or gramophone is obvious.
There is no threat of a collapse in the form of accidentally switched on mobile internet, or the subsequent huge bill for data transfer.
What to Choose
The cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have slots for the removable memory cards (M2, microSD type, etc.).
You can only get up to 2,000 kroner if you add the right card.
But be careful.
The basic types support only cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB or less.
Only the most expensive can get started with up to 8GB of memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and you want to buy a cheap MP3 player, choose Cowont, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or irivert.
Based on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you don't have to spend more than 1 100 kroner.
If you are a more demanding student, choose a specialized mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices also have a separate MP3 control button, which makes it easy to operate and close to the MP3 player.
The industry's most advanced product is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman series of mobile phones have the same user interface as the MP3 players sold separately.
MP3 players from the above brands can provide the same service in the same price range up to SEK 4000, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (generally 15 hours, up to 35 hours).
The first virtual service provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe you
The Czech mobile market is relatively developed and our operators offer virtually the same services as their Western European counterparts.
But we're missing something here -- a virtual service that's forcing traditional providers to make substantial reductions.
Maybe it won't be like this for long.
We have written many times on the Mobil.cz website that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is higher than in other EU countries.
This may lead to a controversial situation after the European Commission's latest move to regulate roaming charges - some Czech mobile phone operators' customers will get cheaper SMS from abroad than from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition that really wants to fight.
This may sound counterintuitive, considering we have three cell phone networks and our penetration is well over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, Chairman of the Board of the Czech Telecommunications Authority, has often agreed with this, having stated on several occasions that there is no place for a new operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network probably has not much chance (and therefore probably would have difficulty finding frequencies).
But there is another option - the virtual provider.
It was the entry of virtual mobile operators that led to a significant price drop, to which the traditional operators had to respond.
Meanwhile, even before big fish like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile in the UK, there were voices like ours.
However, it has been proven that such providers have a place and can indeed succeed.
However, we do not have to look far for an example.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual service provider Mobilking in Poland.
In less than six months, it had managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest provider in the country.
In the meantime, Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which in the Czech Republic owns, among others, U:fon.
The advantage of virtual service providers is that they can focus on a much narrower target group.
It needs far fewer customers than a traditional service provider to operate efficiently.
It is not associated with relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers in the world thus generally appear to be low-cost - offering cheap calls and SMS, but often compensating for this with fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the United Kingdom offers text messages at least 50 percent cheaper than its competitors.
But as the Mobilking case in Poland shows, it can be a good bet to target a target group.
This service is specifically targeted at men.
"Real men choose the Mobilking provider - someone they like, someone they can trust", says David Seibert, CEO of Mobil Entertainment Company, the operator of the virtual service.
It's hard to say whether a similar idea to Poland's will work here.
Vodafone's spokesman, Miroslav Čepický, expresses doubts: 'The Czech market is relatively small for the segmentation approach on which most of the virtual service providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfied with regard to the provision of services.'
No chance in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is going to be a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about a successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not seem very promising.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries of our region", said Jana Studničková, spokesperson for Penta's financial group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
In this way, it indirectly demonstrated that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not overly sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they do their utmost to ensure that no potential competition is created.
The GTS Novera Group has not been hiding its interest in launching the virtual service provider for some time now, and is thus taking another step towards making Telefónica O2 a true competitor in the corporate customer market.
'We are very interested in providing our customers with not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
This possibility was discussed with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations", says Pavel Kaidl, the group's spokesman.
Maybe now is the time for something better.
Unofficial information suggests that we may have our first virtual service provider by the end of the year.
But for now, his birth is surrounded by an impenetrable wall of silence.
'At the moment we do not think that a full-fledged virtual service provider has a place on the Czech market.
The Czech market is very special compared to other markets.
We have not been approached by a single company offering a complex and serious project in this area", Vlastimil Sršeň, from Telefónica's press office, told Mobil.cz.
The other operators also refer to the specific situation of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, T-Mobile spokesperson, agreed with O2 exceptionally, adding: 'We have not yet signed up to a single viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build.'
And he added, "The T-Mobile network is unlikely to have any virtual service providers by the end of the year.
A concrete agreement should be on the table at this moment to be able to think about such a short-term".
Vodafone's focus is on meeting its own 3G licence requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: 'We are open to negotiations with possible virtual service providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
From the customer's point of view, we consider this to be the most profitable.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find partners to build shared networks for high-speed mobile internet.'
Public authorities - in line with service providers
The behaviour of mobile operators is easy to understand, as the entry of another operator would increase competition, lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easy to enter such a competition?
When service providers have something important to do, they can work together, and that's what the U:fon boom was about.
The biggest pressure on the CTU was probably around the birth of T-Mobile's U-phone.
This is evidenced by the publicly available information on the ČTÚ website.
But now, U-phone is a good reason why we should not allow the virtual service provider to enter.
Martina Kemrová added: 'The competitive environment in the mobile market has recently been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile operator.
In view of the nature of the Czech mobile market, it is clear that the entry of a new player into the market and its services will place high demands on it.'
However, given the attitude of mobile operators, it is quite astonishing that the Czech regulators have shown complete indifference.
However, this is not just about the attitude of ČTÚ, which in the Czech Republic - unfortunately, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries - has no right to interfere in economic competition.
The Competition Authority is the only authority to do so.
But the office has a very distinctive approach to the whole problem.
'The entry of a virtual service provider into the mobile market would only be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile service provider and the virtual service provider for the leasing of the necessary infrastructure.
"The Commission has not yet concluded any such contract, as the range of potential bidders was probably not sufficiently interesting for traditional service providers", said Kristián Chlapua, from the external relations department of the Competition Authority.
A statement made by a representative of the service providers would probably not surprise anyone.
But from an agency that is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and also ensure that no one takes advantage of the market, this is more than strange.
In particular, Kristián Chalupa adds: 'In a country where virtual service providers are usually active, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the decline in the price of mobile services.'
However, it is probably not in OHIM's interest to pursue the correct functioning of the market environment and to put pressure on prices.
In this case, it is indeed shocking to see the very tangible consistency in the response of the three mobile operators.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is almost self-evident.
Like gas stations, the exact same gas prices are probably just a matter of chance and tough competition.
'The Office has not detected any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
Neither of the two providers has a leading position, i.e. a proportionately higher responsibility for its market behaviour.
The telecoms regulator is also likely to lack the tools needed to open up the mobile market for virtual operators", Chalupa said.
The presentation of the market leadership is one of the many points of dispute.
There is, of course, an analysis of the relevant markets carried out by ČTU, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, no other Czech operator is in a leading position on such a market.
However, some legal experts offer another approach - the approval of the network operator is always required for the creation of a virtual service provider.
And the mobile operator, relatively logically, has a monopoly on its own network.
So it's necessarily dominant in a certain segment.
But even if we do not accept this argument, it should be a minimum warning to UOHS that three mobile operators are apparently behaving in a similar way.
The complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned GTS Novera) show that they face very similar obstacles in the negotiations with all the service providers.
And blaming the CTU is a relatively common telecommunications ploy that takes the OHS off the case.
We've seen this in a few similar situations.
Unfortunately, the extension of the CTU's competence in the area of economic competition in the telecommunications sector was not transposed into the text of the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, although many experts hoped that this would improve the situation.
The representatives of the UOHS should know this, but they probably have other interests.
It works when no one's watching.
The Czech authorities have not provided any evidence that the Commission has found that the measure is selective.
These companies publish their own price lists for mobile telephony services, but these are only partially public.
Because these are multi-level marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile services.
The price lists of these companies are usually only available to the selected ones.
The magic is that the company is the traditional corporate customer, as opposed to the service provider, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a high-value customer, you will then receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a pre-payment.
"If the cases you are talking about were to occur, it could be a breach of contract terms that we would deal with and that could lead to the termination of cooperation with the company in question", Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
But it is unlikely that any such activity would not have been reported to the responsible persons of the mobile operators.
The three companies in particular may have several thousand customers.
No provider is immune to this type of procedure.
These companies generate a significant profit from their activities and, unlike the real virtual service providers, are not particularly threatened by their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, yet only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name and therefore cannot be fully available to them, as is the case for the general public of mobile operators.'
But that's what the CTU should be getting at least.
In addition, another question arises for the OHIM.
If mobile operators are blind to such a procedure, why are they blocking the birth of the virtual service provider?
It should be noted that OHIM has a relatively strong legal mandate to detect such activity and, if it does not wish to do so, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the service providers that they have not suspected such activity and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're not the most precious
As mentioned several times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has led to a noticeable decrease in the price of services.
Meanwhile, in virtually all countries where virtual providers have emerged, traditional providers have tried to prevent their emergence to a greater or lesser extent.
The arguments they used were virtually the same - too small, possibly too satisfied market, problems with quality of services, etc.
But in developed countries, it was at this point that regulators stepped in, not to protect the interests of the mobile operators, but to protect the interests of their customers.
And then, either through formal measures or through informal pressure, they managed to create the first virtual service provider, which was followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities are handing the whole thing off to each other.
In our experience, we cannot escape the impression that the ambiguous competencies are useful in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider in our country is really coming soon, the Czech mobile market may be on the move again.
If one of the operators were to allow the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS could hardly be indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of further interested parties.
And we may not have any more expensive phones than in the rest of Europe.
There are four new versions of the new Czech anthem.
Choose the Best
Listen to four takes of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek, on the occasion of the Czech Republic Day, solemnly released the new recordings of the national anthem Where Is My Homeland?
The anthem was recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - male or female solo, choir or instrumental.
The song is sung by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The anthem was modified by Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
The iHNed.cz website lists all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national anthem to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
He has previously told Czech Radio that he has deliberately chosen young, representative vocalists who are expressive and popular to sing the solo variations.
"From the very beginning, I tried to make sure that both of them, and later the orchestra, had a clear diction, a clear understanding, and a harmonious sound", he recalled.
The Czech national anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where is my country? was first performed in the Rendi Theatre in 1834 in Josef Kajetán's play Tyl Fidlovačka, supplemented by the music of František Škroup.
It became popular, and people spontaneously adopted it.
The first verse of the song became a natural part of the national anthem after the formation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
After the formation of the independent Czech Republic, it remained one of the seven state symbols.
