The Prague transport company will deliver for the first time on Wednesday with a chip card
Wednesday, October 1st, 2008 will go down in the history of Prague Transportation Company as the date when the first passenger will board the subway, the tram and the bus with an electronic ticket in his pocket instead of a paper ticket.
The coupon is currently available to approximately one hundred thousand holders of Opencard chip cards.
Passengers can purchase 30-day, 90-day and annual coupons (valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time save them on their chip cards at the information centres and depots of the Transport Corporation at the Museum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
The coupons can be purchased online via the website of the Transportation Company www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than 400 customers by this afternoon.
Those who start using e-commerce can forget about the long lines at subway ticket boxes.
The voucher can be purchased online and stored on an Opencard card in one of the thirteen branches of the City Library.
"At these places, passengers have a counter with trained servers to help them shop online and save their voucher on their card", says Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the project.
In addition to the libraries, electronic vouchers will be available for saving on Opencard in some self-serve machines in the lobbies.
What do these vending machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket takers, and passengers may have noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc, and Vltavská metro stations.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty", Opatrný added.
The coupon is controlled by an automaton instead of a driver
The machines that start tomorrow are simple to operate.
All you have to do is insert the Opencard chip card and the previously paid coupon will automatically be saved.
Electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in the surrounding area.
So on the city's commuter trains and bus lines 300 to 499, which primarily serve residents of the central part of the Czech Republic, travel to the capital.
"In the integrated trains in Prague, the conductors are equipped with card readers that also allow them to check the validity of the coupons", explained Filip Drápal of Ropid, the organisation that compiles the timetable of Prague's public transport.
Buses around the city have card readers built into the driver's seat at the ticket office.
When boarding, the driver must therefore not only show the smart card but also place the Opencard in a designated place on the side of the cash register.
The driver checks the validity of the vouchers.
"For example, if a passenger needs to check the validity of coupons, the easiest thing to do is to ask the driver", Drápal added.
Passengers who are not on city buses and will not remember when their voucher expires can go back to the vending machines that save the vouchers on cards.
