The Sudetes wanted a referendum from the U.S.
The Sudeten Germans demanded that Šumava be annexed to the United States in 1945.
This is evident from the letter in the collection of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we at least want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
This is the request that, allegedly, a group of Sudeten Germans made to the president of the United States in 1945.
This is also revealed by a surviving letter from a private archive, now in the collection of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Czechs from Česky Krumlov are asking the US president not to allow the return of the "Shumava County" to Czechia, which was occupied by Hitler under the Munich Agreement.
"We have interpreted the situation correctly and we really want to be sure in the words that the American troops are coming to the German territories not as oppressors and enemies but as liberators", the letter reads, "People who bear the fate of Šumava in their hearts".
Since the annexation of Czechoslovakia to the Sudeten Germans supposedly - with knowledge of the Czech national character - can only give hope of brutality, ruthlessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over the protectorate over Šumava "now and forever".
"We cannot conceive that, regardless of the opinion of four million of its inhabitants, he would regard this territory as a foreign country to us, oppressing and agitating a minority, and contributing in no small measure to the victory of the Allies", the letter states.
