The restless Gebrselassie is about to break her own world record.
Ethiopian Haile Gebrselassie once again showed why he is considered by many to be the best middle- and long-distance runner ever, when he broke his own world record in Berlin on Sunday, becoming the first person to run the 26.2 kilometers in two hours and four minutes.
With a comfortable victory in a flat track in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie improved his previous time of 2:04:26 by 27 seconds, which he achieved in Berlin last year.
By the age of 35, Gebrselassie had set 26 career world records in a variety of distances, winning world championships or setting world records in almost every distance from the 1,500 meters to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie missed the Beijing Olympic marathon for fear that air pollution might worsen his asthmatic problems, which may have been an over-cautious step in retrospect.
Instead, he entered the Berlin marathon.
In almost perfect conditions - in sunny weather, with temperatures of 9°C at the beginning and 13°C at the end - Gebrselassie won on Sunday, at an incredible 2 minutes 56 seconds per kilometre.
Since marathon runners like Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya, who had never run before, switched to longer distances, the marathon record has dropped by more than two minutes in the past decade, since Brazil's Ronaldo da Costa won in Berlin in 1998 with 2:06:05.
After Sunday's victory, Gebrselassie told reporters that two weeks ago, he had a sprain in both legs and hadn't been able to exercise for two weeks.
It's clear that during the forced rest, you were refreshed and not intoxicated.
"I'm so happy", Gebrselassie told reporters. "I'm so happy that you are here.
"Everything was perfect.
I started training again a week ago, and today I had my doubts, but everything worked out fine".
He has received some criticism - particularly from Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rival - that he uses too many props in his races, generally avoids many world-class marathoners, relies on his sprints as if he were running on a track, and places world records before the spirit of competition.
However, this criticism hardly diminishes Gebrselassie's greatness in long-distance running.
Gebrselassie, with the help of four Kenyan sprinters, crossed the finish line in 1:02:04.
Two top Kenyan runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, gave the pace to Gebrselassie after the pace runners ran out of fuel.
With just over three miles (4.8 km) to go, Gebrselassie overtook Kwambai in a final sprint, who finished second in 2:05:36, improving his personal best by five minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Irina Mikitenko, born in Kazakhstan and now a German citizen, finished a remarkable year with the seventh-fastest time of 2:19:19.
The world record is held by Paula Radcliffe of Great Britain with a time of 2:15:25.
Last spring, Mikitenko, 36, won the London Marathon by a surprising 2:24:14.
He was unable to compete at the Beijing Olympics due to an alleged back injury, but he recovered quickly and won the Berlin Marathon, where he improved by five minutes in the individual peak, the third marathon distance he competed in.
He won the race by clever calculation: first, he let a four-man group of Ethiopians and Kenyans break through and take a considerable lead, then he chased after them for about 20 miles [30 km].
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second with a time of 2:21.31 while Helena Kiprop of Kenya finished third with a time of 2:25.01.
A Separate City, Black Pride and the Trials of the Black
In the sprawling theme park of Greater Orlando -- a few miles from everything that's shiny, loud and mighty -- lurks a quiet little town that is the birthplace of the pride and complexity of the African-American experience.
Eatonville, the first all-black city to be incorporated into the country, and the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as it was described in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown leather, 300 good swimmers, a lot of guajas and two schools, no jail".
It's a pilgrimage now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have attended the annual Zora Festival, a series of celebrations in Eatonville in honour of Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet, in many ways, the city he described and made a tourist attraction - which is also featured in the Florida guidebook published by the Federal Writers Project for the Crisis Era - is distinct from its surroundings.
It was as independent, dignified, and closed-minded as it was in the 1930's, when, Hurston writes, Florida's urban blacks were often unwilling to share their true thoughts with white people who "knew so little about us that they didn't know what they were missing".
Even in the year that black presidential candidate Barack Obama is promoting his open discussion of race, many here are wary of outsider gazes.
"We are very careful about how we tell our story", said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident of the town and a member of the oldest church in the city.
"It must be said properly".
Eatonville has long been characterized by the paradox of victory and struggle.
It's a historic model of black resistance, but it's also a community of almost 2,400 people with poverty rates twice the national average.
Part literary hub, part exemplar of the sometimes-deprecated, sometimes-praised, Southern urban black culture that flourished in the shade of oak trees, the result of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the people here are both proud and defensive.
And the image of Eatonville has been important since Zora, (here everyone calls Hurston).
In books written in a frank, strong dialect - such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937) - he introduced his hometown to the world.
Five sections of the Florida Book of Roads have transformed the city, which lies alongside Route 17, a road that leads from the long-forgotten heart of Florida to one of the sites of black history and human drama.
Hurston, who was as brave as a drum in life and literature, introduced his readers to the business of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then to the more trusting spheres.
He wrote: "To the right of the road we find the modern public school, on a brown ground with a white border, with well-kept yards and playgrounds, which Howard Miller looks after, though he can scarcely read or write".
She mentioned the widow Dash's new husband, and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of liquor and anything you need in temporary accommodations".
So in a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville with autonomy, but also with illiteracy, remarriage and sex.
Clearly, Fodor's guide presented it differently.
That description really didn't appeal to everyone.
"Zora told the truth", related Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson girls whom Hurston immortalized by quoting the silly songs men sang about their beauty.
He added: "Some people didn't like it".
Hurston is still remembered here as the lively oddball who often visited home after his family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin recalled that when Hurston stormed into town, he usually arrived unannounced in a dashing Chevy, with cigarettes and long pants, in a city where people still take pride in their dignified dress.
Most people were fascinated by it, Franklin said, but many were disgusted.
"People were always happy to see Zora", said Franklin.
However, on the terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he added, rocking his chair: "He never stayed too long".
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor, and his books were out of print.
It seemed that Eatonville, along with much of the world, had forgotten about him.
Although she was once a popular author, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major commemorations or large public readings in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood how much he enriched the world or what he left us", said Valerie Boyd, author of the 2003 Hurston biography "Cloaked in a Rainbow".
The turning point came in 1980.
Orange County officials wanted to build a five-lane road through the city instead of the two-lane main street, Kennedy Avenue, which played an important role in the life of the community.
Expansion in Orlando has already begun to penetrate Interstate 4 on the city's western border.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period of history.
Among other things, forced integration ended the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950's, the race-mixing struggles of the community were a taste of hate.
"At that time a group of white boys came over and threw oranges and other things at people sitting on the sidewalk", Franklin said.
"There was a lady who died in it.
"They threw a turkey out of a car".
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's decision to mandate forced integration, saying of the Brown v. Board of Education decision, "It is more insulting than respectful of my race".
Now, residents say that while the desegregation of the schools was positive in some ways, it weakened the cohesion of Eatonville and undermined the confidence of the young people.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - the teacher was hugged in the morning and in the evening", reported N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins, executive director of the nonprofit organization We're Watching the Community of Eatonville.
"This continued as long as the students and the teachers were from the same place", he added.
"We didn't hug our white teacher because she was a white teacher - I mean there were cultural differences between us", Nathiri said.
But human rights helped to lift up many other Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors and artists who rose above prejudice, as she did, with such visionary confidence and lines as, "How can anyone deprive themselves of the enjoyment of my company!
It's beyond my comprehension".
In 1975, Alice Walker walked into Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight to restore her reputation.
Five years later, a biography of Robert E. Hemenway, a well-known biographer of Hurston, was placed on bookstore shelves, once again elevating him to the status of an American exemplar.
The road project was about to begin as Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again in the spotlight.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw him as their savior.
In 1988, the community began organizing a Hurston Festival to show what would ruin the county's highway system.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and many have returned to the celebration every January since.
A few years later, the county rejected the proposed road.
"The five-lane highway has brought the community back to life, to full speed, and that's a real civic pride", Nathiri said.
Boyd put it more simply, "Eatonville was saved by the storm".
The victory over the road project helped change the city's self-image.
With more and more out-of-towners showing up, like lawyer Rachelle Munson, who started attending the church in 1993, the locals began to reassess the past.
Eatonville was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1998.
In 2006, the new one-story library (naturally named after Hurston) opened on the renovated and embellished Kennedy Avenue.
Eatonville remains Florida's cockatoo: it's less than 10 miles from downtown Orlando, but sometimes it feels like a suburban back street in the summer rain; it's as small as when 27 black families founded it in the 1880s.
(Today, 90% of the population is black.)
They're still wary of outsiders coming here looking for the story of Eatonville to tell.
Most interviews require prior permission, and some things - such as the oldest fresco in Eatonville, painted by a white man and depicting black men working the land - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville - including the confident teacher Jones, who is particularly drawn to the vibrant red - fear that their separate community will be misunderstood.
And yet, as the Hurston Festival grew in stature, so did the pride of the town.
Young people in particular are increasingly seeing Eatonville the way Hurston saw his own race: as wonderful, with problems and everything, neither better nor worse, just as proud, creative, industrious, foolish and confused as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
There is a genuine civic commitment in the voices of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return after college to take a job with the local government or the police, which he believes are in need of help.
And it seems that the younger ones have learned to describe Eatonville correctly, as did the 11-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alexia Kenon.
"Most people who pass through here think this town is nothing compared to the others", said Alondra Kenon recently after church on a Sunday.
"But if you stop and take a little time to learn about its history, it's a very nice city".
