In his series Flamenco-people, Günther Bauer of Germany combines the theatricality of the singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser-known, everyday side of the masters.
Through the photographs, he presents the unique iconography of flamenco from different angles.
The exhibition, part of Flamenco Photography Month, "reflects the growing international significance of flamenco", says the artist, adding that the Flamenco-people "can be anyone, because the images make the observer realize that these images do not represent the artists in a typical way.
These people who are on the street are artists who can bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and captivate the audience.
Stage photography, however, is not the best way to capture their personalities.
Their personality and character are at the very core of their being.
I wanted to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the great flamenco players with the camera".
The Cante de las Minas Festival gave Bauer the impetus to embark on a long journey in 1997, during which he took portraits of flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers with a flat camera.
This portrait, thanks to the camera and the choice of subject, evokes classic photography.
The use of different stylistic devices, however, breaks with traditional imagery and suggests modernity. The following thought reflects Bauer's idea of flamenco: "It is a music with traditional roots, but one that changes from day to day and is always fascinating".
It is not the dance, nor the singing or the music itself, but rather the personality, the character of the artist that captivates the audience.
The main motive of the works that can be seen today in the El Fotómata Gallery is the search for an encounter with the essence, the artistic illusion, which becomes visible through the way of perception, existence and representation.
The names of well-known flamenco figures, such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, are the names of this collection of photographs, which features almost sixty artists.
