Drunk drivers will be required to install the Alcolock
The Department of the Interior would require a driver to install a device that would prevent the vehicle from starting when the driver is drunk or not breathing into the device after three DUI violations.
The proposal was submitted in June and is currently being examined by the Public Prosecutor's Office, which says the pilot project will last for one year.
As the aim of the project is to restore the vehicle to traffic, the driver will also have to attend a repeated course on traffic education.
The pilot will involve the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Foundation for Automotive Safety Technology (FITSA), in addition to the Attorney-General's Office.
Statistics show that 30 to 75 percent of drivers who are repeatedly arrested for DUI are getting back into their cars.
The Alcolock would prevent this, because the system connected to the vehicle would detect the alcohol level of the air injected. If it is higher than the permitted level or if the driver does not inhale the device at all, the system will not allow the car to start.
The cost of the device, which is over 1000 euros, would be borne by the offender.
A related 2007 study in the USA demonstrated that vehicles equipped with such devices can reduce the number of infringements by up to 65% in the first year after installation.
In Spain, it is estimated that this rule could save 115 lives a year.
The measure focuses on breaches of the rules for two reasons: firstly, it makes it easier to prevent them from becoming criminal offences;
On the other hand, it is easier to introduce, as the implementation of legal reform is carried out in the usual way, whereas the necessary criminal reform would require an amendment of the Basic Law.
The apparatus is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although it has already been installed in some industrial and public vehicles in experimental mode.
The House of Representatives will vote tomorrow on the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party's initiative to install the system in school buses, following the French model.
