The Blood Is Safe Again
Héma-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday, and President Dr. Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood donation companies in the world.
Most important, he was able to regain the public trust that had been badly shaken by the contaminated blood scandal of the 1980's and 1990's.
As is well known, the national blood bank maintained by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Service was infected with HIV and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and the general uproar, the Canadian government launched a formal investigation in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to formulate recommendations for preventing future similar cases.
While Justice Krever was late in submitting his report, some provinces formed their own committees to design a new blood-treatment system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Commission carried out this task.
The Gélineau and Krever reports led to the creation of two blood services in Canada: Héma-Québec, which serves Québec, and the Canadian Blood Services Corporation, which serves all other provinces and two territories.
"When Héma-Québec began its work in 1998, just 38 percent of people had confidence in the Québec blood-supply system", recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was desperate.
"In the years that followed, however, the improvement in the safety of blood products and our work in the field have helped us to regain the trust of the people". Décary proudly reports that by early 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population had trusted Héma-Québec.
But Dr. Décary does not forget that "trust is a very fragile thing".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
During this period, several cases of human infection with a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease were detected in Europe, says Dr. Gerhardt, who has been running the association since it was founded in 1998.
"We had no idea that this disease was transmitted by blood.
So we took one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which is that if we are unsure and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, we should take exclusionary measures, and in this case it was Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which causes brain damage, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, we did not accept blood from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
And a few years ago, it was established beyond all doubt that the disease is also transmitted through the blood.
This case convinced us that the precautionary principle was a good idea".
In 1999 a technique was introduced that allows for a much more sensitive diagnosis of HIV - a nucleic acid assay (NAT) that can detect the virus directly in the blood of donors, rather than the antibodies against the virus that previous tests were based on.
"With the NAT test, we have shortened the window period from infection to when we can detect the virus in the blood with our technology", he explains.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
This greatly reduced the risk of unknowingly infecting the blood supply by donors and of its being undetectable.
These developments have greatly reduced the risk of AIDS transmission through blood transfusions.
Today, the odds of someone getting blood contaminated with HIV are 12 million to one.
"In other words, that means we would have to distribute 12 million units of blood until someone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 units of blood annually, it would take more than 24 years for one such case to occur and for someone to become infected with HIV through a unit of blood.
"I think that today, anyone can accept or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore health", says the number one leader of Héma-Québec.
"The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what new pathogen is getting into the system.
It was only last year that the Chikungunya virus, which like the West Nile virus is transmitted through insect bites, appeared on the island of Réunion.
We must be on the alert at all times,' Dr Décary continued, and stressed that besides emergency reserves, Héma-Québec must have a sufficient permanent reserve.
"As the population ages, so do the needs.
As cancer-fighting treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population is also affecting the donor pool, since only 3% of Quebec's population is in the network of eligible donors.
However, any healthy person who is at least 18 years of age and who meets the eligibility requirements can give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of the applicants refuse to accept blood because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have been in a country where malaria is rampant are not eligible to donate blood for a year.
"With that 3 percent, we have enough in reserve to meet the needs of the hospitals.
It's very rare for us to run out of supplies.
But we need to increase the number of donors as the existing ones get older, because after a while, they can't give blood.
But it's very difficult to convince people to donate blood, and it's even harder to keep them and get them to become regular blood donors.
In today's fast-paced world, one has barely an hour to go and give blood", laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissues, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeball tissue, and skin tissue, almost exclusively for use in the treatment of severe burns.
These tissues are analysed, transformed and frozen, and then deposited at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public stem cell bank in Québec.
The cord, now treated as medical waste, can be used to extract blood rich in stem cells, which can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated the arrival of the thousandth cord blood sample in our bank a few weeks ago, and we plan to collect over a thousand new samples each year.
"We are going to start offering them for transplantation early next year", says Dr. Décary, who says that cord blood donation is very popular today.
'Many mothers are sad that they don't have the opportunity' - and this is true, because Héma-Québec cannot afford to make this complex and expensive program available in all hospitals in Québec.
