Opinion - The Orwellian oration of Barrick Gold
A letter from Patrick J. Garver, deputy president and chief executive officer of the Canadian Barrick Gold Mine, was published in the September 17 issue of Le Devoir.
Following Orwell's rant, Garver states that the world's largest gold-producing company has filed a $6 million libel suit against three authors and a small-cap publishing company for the purpose of initiating a so-called "public debate".
Although the judges are independent and impartial, they base their decisions - especially in defamation cases - not on truth but on the law.
It's no wonder Garver was silent about this fundamental difference.
Is it really the best way for Barrick Gold to engage in public debate to destroy anyone who disagrees with their position?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publishers of Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums of money to defend and fight an unequal fight with an army of lawyers on the other side, supported by the mining industry's almost inexhaustible resources.
In such an unequal fight, however, the tactic of undermining the plaintiff and making friendly settlements is often employed, not only to silence opponents but even to intimidate those who would try to re-open the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have spoken to the public.
Although this is not the case in many other countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, the parties to a dispute usually do not strike each other with a club but speak their minds.
So all the mine had to do was open up its books and files and prepare for a real debate in the press, media, publications, paying independent research groups to shed light on the issue.
But it seems that Barrick Gold doesn't trust the public and is throwing out petitions and letters written in defense of Noir Canada's authors with a motion.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain to me how he could initiate a "public" debate while ignoring the views of that public?
In the vice president's mind, the word probably means only the lavishly paid lawyers and not the entire population of Canada, and the meaning of the term is much reduced.
In a democratic state, even those who speak ill of others have the right to free speech.
Barrick Gold, on the other hand, doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - that the main reason why the authors and publishers of Noir Canada are supported by the public is because they condemn the mine's brutal methods.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and make a judgment, but on the basis of civilized reasoning, rather than through a lawsuit that many would prefer to silence (and, incidentally, in connection with the term "public debate", Barrick Gold recently wrote to Noir Canada's authors to ask them to refrain from using that term.)
Beyond Garver's surreal arguments, the Barrick Gold case is an open attack on the freedom of academic inquiry and the pursuit of truth that are the building blocks of any democratic society.
In the process as a whole, it denies the right to cite credible sources, to debate facts and their interpretation, which are the basis of intellectual activities.
If a country like Canada can only study and discuss topics that are frowned upon by the corporate world of today, who will dare to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted an open and transparent debate, it could do so according to the scientific standards that the authors of Noir Canada use.
You have the right to answer.
We have long been able to handle debates, disagreements and conflicts in our academic circles.
Barrick Gold's reckless conduct clearly shows that, contrary to his assertions, he is not inclined to engage in open debate.
This is a loss for both the academic world and the Canadian public debate institution, and it is time for governments to implement measures that limit the legal process for such abuse.
