What was produced in the Zuschlag & Tsai factory?
Soon, on October 8, the trial of the criminal case against János Zuschlag and his associates will begin.
The politician and his associates are accused of fraud and other crimes, including forgery of documents, in a criminal organisation and in a businesslike manner, causing particularly significant damage.
According to the prosecution, the funds received from the tender were used for their own purposes, and the completion of the tasks was often confirmed by fake invoices.
The state and municipal funds - totalling some HUF 65 million - went partly to the cash register of the Young Left and partly to the pockets of individuals.
The method described by the investigating authority was that the tender money was collected on the basis of cost statements that were not backed by real performance and the associations never fulfilled the obligation undertaken.
The indictment says most of the bills were fake.
The bills were obtained from the market in Josephsburg, and the postage stamps were produced in Kiskunhalas.
And which companies the invoices were issued to, among other things, on the route to the Balaton area, where Zuschlag sent István Lados.
The latter confessed to looking for inns and restaurants.
He requested an invoice for his consumption there, which was then used to prepare invoices to be submitted to the applications of, among others, the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Social and Labour Fund, and the Metropolitan Municipality.
Most of these were written by István Lados with his colleague, András Őri, who, according to our information, wrote mostly the reports necessary to obtain the grants.
One of the highlights of Lados' "study trip" was a bar.
According to two invoices issued by the Zuschlag family in 2003, the restaurant catered for a group of 90 persons belonging to the Sigur Point Association.
However, according to the manager, that number would not have entered the restaurant at one time.
Similarly, the invoice for the Better Future - later called Together for the Third Millennium - Foundation issued in the summer of 2002 was riddled with errors of form and content.
A boarding house in Badacsony had only three rooms, and no more than ten people could sleep in it for one night, but the number was one hundred and thirty guests.
