The psychology of over-bidding: why are we spending more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overvalue the goods.
The neuroeconomic basis for this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior has been uncovered by neuroscientists and economists at New York University.
Their study, published in the journal Science, says that people are willing to pay a premium for a competitive product, such as an eBay auction, if they don't want to be outdone.
The research attempted to map the neural circuitry of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers participated in a lottery, while the other participated in a toy auction, while the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method examined the active brain areas of the subjects.
Both games offered money, but in the auction game, where the over-bidding of the other party is a major element, the striatum, a complex under the brain's cortex, became actively involved when the game was lost.
This area of the brain plays a role in the "self-reward" mechanism of the nervous system, among other functions.
Therefore, the researchers believe that the increase in price can be explained by avoiding a violent reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the economists in the research group also conducted a financial impact study.
In this case, three groups bid against a partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they did their thing.
Another group was also promised a $15 bonus if they won the game.
The third group, on the other hand, had just received $15 before the auction, but the members of the group lost that money in a losing auction.
So the only difference between the two groups was that one group was emphasized on winning, and the other group was emphasized on losing.
However, proving the neurologists' hypothesis, members of the "lose-lose" teams were willing to bet even higher than the control and "win-win" groups.
"These results cannot be deduced from any pre-existing economic theory.
For until now, they have explained the phenomena of auctioning solely by the joy of winning and the avoidance of risk.
Only neurological imaging techniques have helped to resolve the conflict between these two theories, and now we have a third explanation", stated Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: when should I see a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infections, and chronic liver disease is listed as a leading cause of death in Hungary.
There are hundreds of thousands of people infected with hepatitis here, but only 7,000 are being treated, and the reason is that patients often don't know they're infected.
The term hepatitis is a collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
They have many similarities in symptoms, typically hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases they cause are different.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways, depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E are transmitted through the digestive tract (e. g., through contaminated food, water), and hepatitis B, C, D, and the other viruses are transmitted through blood and body fluids (feces, vaginal excrement, saliva).
Travellers should be vaccinated against A and B viruses, but there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating the infected food, generally accompanied by nausea, weakness, stomach complaints, nausea.
After this, the skin and whites of the eyes turn yellow, the stool is light, the urine turns dark, and the healing process may take two or three weeks.
One million people a year die worldwide from the more severe form of the disease, hepatitis B, caused by liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten people infected with the virus receive treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis, even liver cancer.
Most people who are infected are unaware of their disease, for the virus subtly destroys the cells of the liver, often taking 20 to 30 years for the first symptoms to appear.
So it's very important to do early prevention, to do regular screening.
Three groups have a much higher rate of this disease than the average: transfused people before 1991, people who use drugs, and people who have tattoos.
Worldwide, there are an estimated 200 million people who are chronically infected with the hepatitis C virus.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory test, it is advisable to consult your doctor if you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Early detection of the disease can be cured, the virus can be eliminated from the body, thus eliminating infectiousness and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first celebrated in 2004 by organizations representing patients around the world.
It aims to raise awareness of chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, its causes and the importance of early detection.
Does believing in God make you feel less pain?
Recent research has found that religious faith acts as a kind of painkiller, which may have facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment to examine how belief in God affects people's perception of pain, reports the Telegraph of England.
In a rather bizarre experiment, 12 Catholics and an equal number of atheists were electrocuted while all of them were studying a painting of the Virgin Mary.
The results showed that the Catholic faithful were able to exclude much of the pain.
The human brain scan technique also revealed that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
The study is the first in a series of studies involving academics, as well as scientists, philosophers, and theologians from across the university.
The test was carried out precisely by attaching a sparkler device to the subject's left hand, which was the source of the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants to look intently at two paintings, a 17th-century painting by Sassoferrato, and a 15th-century painting by Leonardo da Vinci, Lady Hermeline.
The study's authors hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary would evoke a religious mood among believers, while the da Vinci image was chosen because it was not too different from the others and was thought to have a calming effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, during which time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive sessions, while looking at either the religious-themed or the general image.
Catholics reported that they felt "safe" and "protected" and "calm and at peace" during visions of the Virgin Mary.
The religious-themed viewers reported 12 percent less pain than when they were looking at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who was involved in the study, believes that the same effect can be achieved with any powerful image, even for atheists, just by finding the right photo.
"We should find an image that makes people feel very positive about them, like a mother or a father", the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the findings.
"The practice of faith should and often does change our personality", added Wright.
After these wonderful results, the question is, if you showed the faithful a painting of the Madonna by Leonardo or a similar artist, what effect would that have on their pain management?
Would a vision of the Virgin Mary have better results?
You are what you share about yourself
On its 10th birthday, Google can tell you that it's in people's pockets as much as it is in the sky above them; it knows where they've been on vacation, what they've been to, and what they're interested in.
And that's still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's top people.
And for the skeptics who are drawing parallels with Orwell's nightmare, they're the ones who are missing the point of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's primary goal is to collect even more personal data about its users, and that this is necessary to keep them in line with the original goal of the Google founders, which was to "put all the world's information in a system".
The Google boss said that after ten years of world-changing work, the company is just getting started on all the information it can handle.
Asked what it would be like in five years, Schmidt said he wished Google could answer questions like "what am I going to do tomorrow?" or "what kind of job is right for me?" - but until then, software can't answer these seemingly simple questions because it doesn't know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that Internet searches record the exact words used, the IP address from which they were searched and the page to which the interested party went after the search.
Personalized Search, which was launched two years ago, allows users to store their browsing history, look back on what they've searched for, what they've clicked on, and in the long run, generate much more personalized results for them - the same logic that Recommendations will use to recommend products and services to us based on our previously stated and recorded preferences.
What if they use my data against me, what if they see what I do? - users ask, worried about Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, it's the potential power of the corporation that's scary, not the guilt, not the fear of punishment, the desire for freedom, maybe the rebellion against power that's driving the online reaction.
However, it is a well-established fact that all search terms are not only recorded but may also be passed on to third parties where appropriate, and in such legal cases the privacy rights of Internet users are not protected.
Perhaps the most prominent recent example of this was the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, in which Google provided the Brazilian government with identifiable information about pedophiles from its Orkut social network.
Privacy-conscious netizens were able to mount a legal challenge in May when the company, in partnership with the EFF, successfully argued in court against the FBI that Google could not be forced by any provision of the Constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(However, the federal government successfully fought off some fifty thousand web addresses and a thousand search terms it had obtained by invoking the Child Protection Act passed years earlier, but it still failed to obtain search lists of individual users or a complete web site and keyword list spanning two months.)
So Google's judgment is quite controversial: it is scolded by those who are afraid to give their personal information because they feel that their privacy is being violated by using Google's services and by rebelling against them with the image of a corporation that is glowing in conservative images.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its drive to bring together computer enthusiasts, activists, users in many countries, is seeing the next generation of big companies, the "leading corporation", as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, which has emerged as a world leader because of Windows, even though both are fighting for the same goal.
It's because Google, unlike Microsoft, doesn't ask for user IDs, doesn't charge for its applications, and the open source, free, continuously updated software package is more accessible, more youthful, and cooler than the official software giant's practices.
But it can also be because geeks have a clear understanding of the very problematic relationship between privacy rights and the Internet, which has been followed by one of the most frequently used keywords of recent years, web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, about intentionally leaving traces and taking advantage of the communication channels that are available to us, and while the scale of these varies from individual to individual, the essence is the same: show yourself.
The average young person can also have a profile on multiple social networks, from Facebook to Twitter, linking them to other services like Twitter or last.fm, which lists their music habits, linking them to social media like FriendFeed or Blip.fm, and blogging, where they automatically see their latest photo galleries from Flickr or Picasa.
While there are many examples of this, the friend can easily figure out who her cheating boyfriend spent the night with by looking at the photo gallery of their shared morning circle of friends, or can fire a company employee just because he writes an honest opinion on his blog about top management: one sure is that the notion of privacy has been completely overvalued.
Living an online life is about what you show, and that's the foundation of what's going on with today's youth.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least want to avoid the Google monopoly, can do so (starting with, for example, the Scroogle who uses the Google search engine but at the same time intentionally leaves no trace).
For example, many people who intentionally don't log on to social media so they can't be found, Google's online applications, from text editors to image editors to newsreaders, can be replaced by alternative versions that aren't tied to giant server farms and that don't build the best profile of us that's ever existed.
The public isn't exactly waiting in secret for Google to show off its tooth whites.
With a current value of $156 billion, it is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising platforms threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, and the accelerating pace of services introduction is causing serious headaches not only for Microsoft but also for many other software developers.
Critical observers, however, find the counter-arguments to be troubling: for example, the top management completely rejected the employees' protest after doubling the company's kindergarten fee, the company management found it too expensive to feed the employees multiple times a day, but all this is overshadowed by the fact that Google had to bow to the Chinese government in 2006 and under their agreement the company filtered all findings that hurt the good taste or the interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the company's internal rules is that they don't announce new services until they're ready to use them, but what they're sure to do is to take the problems that are coming up in the next few months and years and move the world to a new place: while some people think that Google's book and magazine scanning and archiving project has reached a point where the company will soon have to face the US Supreme Court, others are terrified of the Health system, because it allows us to build a complete health profile of ourselves with our past records, our doctors and our problems.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database, which could be a good source material for the next generation of science fiction writers, is that Cory Doctorow's popular novel, Scroogled Point, describes in Orwellian tones a future in which a human being can only be approached from Google data in a frighteningly good way.
