The intelligent car imitates the flight of the dongo
What better way to develop collision avoidance technologies than by imitating natural obstacle detectors?
Like the bees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the bumble bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic starting idea for how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimicrobot control system, a robotic mini-car endowed with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that eliminates all collisions.
"In flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety shell", explained Kazuhiro Doi, a technology PR and R&D brand manager at the exhibition.
The bee's complex eye, which can see more than 300 degrees in all directions, plays a vital role.
To replicate the function of the complex eye, engineers have turned to the idea of a laser telescope.
This identifies obstacles within 2 metres of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance, and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts into a collision avoidance action.
In a fraction of a second, the obstacle is detected and the robot, mimicking the movement of the womb, immediately changes direction by turning its wheels as needed to avoid the collision.
Unlike any current system, this evasive maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If this were not the case, the car-robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car-robot project.
It must react spontaneously and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety guard, a layer within which a collision is currently considered to be unavoidable.
The whole process should mirror what one bee does in order to avoid other bees.
This process should take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike the spokes, the deviation can't be up, down or transverse, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction of the rotation of the wheels.
So instead of the endless possibilities for bees to avoid other bees, here we just use the rotary motion and acceleration and deceleration as options for the Autobot.
BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries which are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer life than the lithium-ion version.
Andoh believes that instinctive intelligence is the ability to process, much less store, information.
This device only needs to process and respond to a few input signals per second.
It doesn't need to store them, and it reacts with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it only uses a few dozen kilobytes of memory all the time.
You don't need gigabytes of memory, or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in developing the immediate escape technology that Nissan estimates could be in production within ten years.
Another possible application is to integrate the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to guide the car to the specified destination by avoiding obstacles in the road.
