Today, the European Equal Opportunities Summit began in Paris, hosted by France, which holds the Presidency of the European Union this year.
In her message to the plenary, Járóka Lívia, a member of the European People's Party, and one of the main speakers at the professional conference, drew attention to educational segregation as one of the most serious violations of rights affecting Roma children and, moreover, the most serious obstacle to their enforcement.
The high-level conference was opened by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities, on behalf of the French Presidency.
The conference was attended by representatives of governments, the European social partners and the most important European human rights and civil society organisations in the field of equal opportunities.
Járóka warned that, in addition to discrimination in employment, Roma were excluded from the labour market mainly because of their low level of education.
"The overwhelming majority of Roma youth do not have a secondary education and only a minority can obtain higher education because of the poor quality of their primary education".
Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a key role in the promotion of other human rights.
Investing in early education for Roma children can be a boost to the economies of the EU Member States.
The MEP believes that these links should be made known to the widest possible audience, including Roma and non-Roma.
The earlier a Roma student starts school, the greater his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market; they contribute to the national budget through income and consumption taxes.
"The Roma should be guaranteed their right to quality education as citizens of the European Union and the elimination of their low-quality and segregated education should be guaranteed", Járóka Lívia stressed.
The MEPs also stressed that the EU should be able to take action to ensure that the right to vote is respected, and that the right to vote should be respected in all Member States.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, and give Roma children the opportunities that the democratic space has given them, so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens", Járóka demanded.
The European Summit on Equal Opportunities, which has been held annually since the last Berlin meeting in the framework of the 'European Year of Equal Opportunities for All', aims to provide a unique forum for promoting the objectives of equal opportunities and non-discrimination at European and Member State level.
