The Elite in Danger
And you could see it a few days ago when the House of Representatives didn't vote on the $700 billion bailout package that the White House put forward, and a significant portion of the American people were more interested, and still are, in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is backed up by yesterday's New York Times reporting that the current crisis has created a rift within the Republican Party, revealing a growing divide between the traditional, conservative East Coast attitude of support for federal institutions and business and the new, anti-Washington and anti-financial world that is growing in the Midwest and South.
This line was critically manifested in the House of Representatives vote mentioned in the introduction.
But this is only one of the many changes that the economic transformation that is still taking place is foreshadowing or making visible, not only in the United States but throughout the Western world and perhaps beyond.
It seems that the crisis, both in the US and in Europe, is only accelerating the phenomena that have been latent for a long time, which are consolidating in this new atmosphere and are finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the return of the dual category of state sovereignty to the public consciousness, in connection with a kind of re-empowerment of the economy.
The crisis is affecting banking and financial institutions, which, although they have close links with the rest of the world, are primarily and largely affected by individuals and families who live in one country, one state.
This, in turn, creates a direct political difficulty for those in power to respond to the grievances and protests of the people who are also voters.
So while the crisis may seem global in an economic sense, it is almost entirely national in a political sense.
Political internationalism seems to be essentially stranded beyond the shore: the European Union is a clear example of this, which, floundering between different interests and divergent national strategies, is unable to set a unified political direction.
So everyone is waiting for the national governments to intervene, to provide a bailout, to resuscitate and to set new rules, but above all to open up the money markets: because in a tight situation, only the individual states have the economic resources, the financial reserves, that might be able to make things right.
They have the means and the authority to use them: under the circumstances, they have two invaluable resources that no other market and no international organisation will ever have in such quantity.
The new emphasis on the nation-state in the context of the crisis is also fully consistent with the fact that recent economic growth has given greater importance to a factor closely linked to this element: territorial dimension.
And paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had entered the network, the abstract world of increasingly sophisticated technology, and we were convinced that the global financial world was destined to dominate the world, we were suddenly forced to realize that our future was increasingly dependent on things that were not at all abstract, like water, crops and oil.
Things that can be transported from one side of the planet to the other, yet are completely tied to a particular place, a particular area.
So the person who dominates the territory has a lot more cards than the person who unfortunately was born in a place where there is no crops, no oil and no water.
And that brings me to the second innovation, which is a kind of a breakthrough.
When you say territory, state, government, you are necessarily saying politics, or in other words, leadership.
From this point of view, the economic crisis seems to produce two interlocking phenomena:
On the one hand, an objective recognition that we need authentic leadership, people who can take charge of events.
On the other hand, the current leadership, especially the business leaders, have been completely discredited, they have proven to be completely incompetent and they have proven that there is still a lot of uncertainty ahead.
The two together have a deeper meaning and are in some ways more disturbing: the sense of loss of trust, impatience, incompetence and alienation that is affecting the entire leadership elite in an increasing number of Western countries.
So it seems that there is a growing belief among the general population that the era of the social elite, which was at its peak, is over, that it is over before they can adopt their actions, their experiences, their way of life, their culture, in the complex sense of the word, and that the social elite is becoming increasingly alienated from the majority opinion.
In other words, the need for leadership, in its veiled form, is fueling a widespread but strong delegitimization movement against the ruling class and the traditional political system, which is manifested in unexpected "uprisings" of voters, or in recent times in sudden shifts in public sentiment, such as the rise to power of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of the unity of the workers' party in Britain, or the revolt of the US congressmen against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the Italian right).
It seems that the traditional elite, with its parties, its programs, and, one might even say, with its habits, its press and its elite intellectuals, is becoming less and less able to understand and therefore less and less able to represent what has been going on in the deeper layers of Western society for some time.
Yet, to speak of "the revolt of the masses on the threshold" would be an exaggeration, to be frank.
