That energy comes from the waves, and now the big ones are coming.
An inexhaustible source of energy that covers 70 percent of the planet's surface and is only now being discovered by the major international energy companies.
Waves, ocean currents, tides, all renewable energy sources that giants like Chevron have set their sights on, and are now trying to get their hands on.
For a hundred years, scientists have been exploring the possibility of harnessing the power of the ocean's movements.
Around 1980, when oil prices fell, the idea of using offshore energy was abandoned, but today environmental concerns and the renewed rise in oil prices are giving new impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be met by offshore wind turbines.
That's twice the amount of energy produced by nuclear power plants today.
Besides, there'd be currents and tides.
The giants are in action.
Enersis was the first company to commit to offshore energy, signing an agreement in 2005 for a power plant in Northern Portugal.
It seemed like a revolutionary move when the signing was announced.
Two years have passed since then, and more and more companies are now voting for marine energy, including those who until now have been committed supporters of conventional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean-based energy technologies and is considering working with us", a spokesman for one of the U.S. oil giant's joint ventures told the Wall Street Journal.
The cooperation in question concerns the acquisition of a license issued by the US Energy Commission for the launch of a marine energy project in Alaska.
This is not insignificant, especially when you consider that the United States is drilling for oil in Alaska, and President Bush has recently launched a plan to drill for more.
Besides Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are also pursuing offshore energy, and the amount of money invested so far, as far as the details are known, is indicative of growing interest.
The technology is still being developed.
Experts say the technology is still in its infancy, simply because the energy from the sea does not dispel concerns about its environmental impact.
The existing facilities, such as those in Portugal and Scotland, are all small and therefore not very problematic for the ecosystem.
However, to produce energy on a larger scale, facilities are needed that also have a greater environmental impact.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power uses an interconnected buoy system, for example.
The shock of the waves that moves the buoys up and down is converted into hydraulic pressure by the piston and cylinders.
The pressure drives a turbine, which drives a generator.
Electricity is carried to land by undersea cables.
There are currently four similar facilities in the planning stages, all of which are awaiting federal approval, and some of the energy produced would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started generating power for a shopping mall and a parking lot with six subsea turbines located in New York's East River estuary.
When the water is in the flow, the turbine rotates, and this rotation powers the generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of partners who are just waiting for the necessary permits to use the energy.
Waves and waves.
At present, the opportunities that tidal currents offer deserve special attention.
Although it is a temporary phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than the wind, the sun, or the waves, and thus can be considered a more reliable source of energy.
New York, Maine, Alaska, and other coastal states spent $7.5 million in 2008 to harness the power of tides, and that number is projected to grow to $35 million in 2009.
